I have tried to format object  value into DateTime using TryParseExact() method but this method will always returns false. I have used the below codes,

 private void Button_Click(object sender, RoutedEventArgs e)
        {
           object cellValue;
            DateTime columnValue;
            cellValue = new DateTime(1999, 1, 13, 3, 57, 32, 10); 
            if(DateTime.TryParseExact(cellValue.ToString(), "hh:mm:ss.fff", CultureInfo.InvariantCulture, DateTimeStyles.None, out columnValue))
            {
                MessageBox.Show(columnValue.ToString());
            }
            else
            {
                MessageBox.Show("Wrong value");
            }
        }

I need to convert the DateTime value with milliseconds. 
Can you kindly provide any solution for this ?

Code: https://github.com/dotnet/wpf/blob/89d172db0b7a192de720c6cfba5e28a1e7d46123/src/Microsoft.DotNet.Wpf/src/Themes/Shared/Microsoft/Windows/Themes/DataGridHeaderBorder.cs#L365

The logic is backwards in that it only caches if the indexed value is _not_ null, versus caching if the indexed value _is_ null. This will result in freezable values never being cached and any calls to GetCachedFreezable will always return a null value causing brushes to be created every time a rendering pass is performed for the specific theme.

The code should instead be:

```csharp
        private static void CacheFreezable(Freezable freezable, int index)
        {
            Debug.Assert(freezable.IsFrozen, "Cached Freezables should be frozen.");

            lock (_cacheAccess)
            {
                if (_freezableCache[index] == null)
                {
                    _freezableCache[index] = freezable;
                }
            }
        }
```
